Fast Second-Order Online Kernel Learning through Incremental Matrix Sketching and Decomposition

Dongxie Wen Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina 2019202221@ruc.edu.cn ,Â  Xiao Zhang Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina zhangx89@ruc.edu.cn Â andÂ  Zhewei Wei Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina zhewei@ruc.edu.cn
(2018)
Abstract.

Online Kernel Learning (OKL) has attracted considerable research interest due to its promising predictive performance in streaming environments. Second-order approaches are particularly appealing for OKL as they often offer substantial improvements in regret guarantees. However, existing second-order OKL approaches suffer from at least quadratic time complexity with respect to the pre-set budget, rendering them unsuitable for meeting the real-time demands of large-scale streaming recommender systems. The singular value decomposition required to obtain explicit feature mapping is also computationally expensive due to the complete decomposition process. Moreover, the absence of incremental updates to manage approximate kernel space causes these algorithms to perform poorly in adversarial environments and real-world streaming recommendation datasets. To address these issues, we propose FORKS, a fast incremental matrix sketching and decomposition approach tailored for second-order OKL. FORKS constructs an incremental maintenance paradigm for second-order kernelized gradient descent, which includes incremental matrix sketching for kernel approximation and incremental matrix decomposition for explicit feature mapping construction. Theoretical analysis demonstrates that FORKS achieves a logarithmic regret guarantee on par with other second-order approaches while maintaining a linear time complexity w.r.t. the budget, significantly enhancing efficiency over existing approaches. We validate the performance of FORKS through extensive experiments conducted on real-world streaming recommendation datasets, demonstrating its superior scalability and robustness against adversarial attacks.

online kernel learning; matrix sketching; streaming recommendation

1. Introduction

Online learning has been extensively applied in streaming recommender systems, where models require frequent updates based on real-time user feedback. In these settings, the processes of training and testing are interwovenÂ (Shalev-Shwartz, 2011; Chandramouli etÂ al., 2011; Chang etÂ al., 2017; Wang etÂ al., 2018b; Jakomin etÂ al., 2020; Zhang etÂ al., 2021; Wang etÂ al., 2018a). A widely adopted algorithm in this domain is Online Gradient Descent (OGD), which iteratively adjusts model parameters by moving in the direction of the negative gradient to minimize the loss functionÂ (Zinkevich, 2003). However, OGD is limited by its reliance on linear combinations of input features, which can be insufficient for capturing complex patterns in real-world streaming recommendation scenarios. To address this shortcoming, Online Kernel Learning (OKL) extends OGD by mapping input features into a high-dimensional reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS), enabling more effective handling of nonlinear learning tasksÂ (Kivinen etÂ al., 2004; Lu etÂ al., 2016b; Singh etÂ al., 2012; Sahoo etÂ al., 2019; Hu etÂ al., 2015).

OKL can be categorized into first-order and second-order approaches. First-order algorithms use a fixed learning rate for gradient descent, resulting in Oâ¢(T)ğ‘‚ğ‘‡O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ) regret for any arbitrary sequence of convex lossesÂ (Lu etÂ al., 2016b; Cavallanti etÂ al., 2007; Zhao etÂ al., 2012; Orabona etÂ al., 2008; Zhang and Liao, 2019), where Tğ‘‡Titalic_T denotes the number of rounds. Although some works set a more aggressive learning rate to improve the regret bound to Oâ¢(logâ¡T)ğ‘‚ğ‘‡O(\log T)italic_O ( roman_log italic_T ), it requires the assumption that the loss function exhibits strong convexity, which is unrealistic for most loss functionsÂ (Zhu and Xu, 2015). In contrast, second-order algorithms utilize the Hessian matrix to adapt the learning rate, achieving logarithmic regret without requiring strong convexity in all directionsÂ (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017b, a; Zhdanov and Kalnishkan, 2013; Hazan etÂ al., 2007).

Despite its improved regret bounds, second-order Online Kernel Learning (OKL) encounters two significant challenges in streaming recommendation systems. First, streaming recommendation applications demand both efficient updates and minimal storage consumption. However, exact second-order OKL incurs Oâ¢(t2)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘¡2O(t^{2})italic_O ( italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) space and time complexity at round tğ‘¡titalic_t, as it requires storing the entire kernel matrixÂ (Hazan etÂ al., 2007; Zhdanov and Kalnishkan, 2013). While some methods employ online sampling techniques to improve efficiency, these approaches primarily focus on kernel matrix approximation and fail to effectively obtain explicit feature mappingsÂ (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017a, b). Specifically, these methods rely on complete singular value decomposition (SVD) to derive explicit feature mappings, which is computationally expensive. Second, real-world applications are often dynamic, reflecting the evolving interests of users over time. For instance, studies have shown that user click behaviors for news articles change over time in both Google NewsÂ (Liu etÂ al., 2010) and Yahoo NewsÂ (Zeng etÂ al., 2016). Without the capability to perform incremental updates in the approximate kernel matrix, existing algorithms risk making suboptimal decisions based on outdated information.

In this paper, we propose a fast incremental matrix sketching approach for second-order online kernel learning, along with an efficient decomposition method designed for incremental updates, effectively addressing the two aforementioned challenges both theoretically and experimentally. Our contributions can be summarized as follows:

  • â€¢

    We propose FORKS, a fast and effective second-order online kernel learning method that can be generalized to both regression and classification tasks in streaming recommendation. FORKS maintains incremental matrix sketching using efficient low-rank modifications and constructs an effective time-varying explicit feature mapping. We provide a detailed theoretical analysis to illustrate the advantages of FORKS, including having linear time complexity w.r.t. the budget, and enjoying a logarithmic regret bound.

  • â€¢

    We propose TISVD, a novel Truncated Incremental Singular Value Decomposition adapting to matrix decomposition problems in online learning environments. We theoretically compare the time complexity between TISVD and the original truncated low-rank SVD, confirming that FORKS with TISVD is computationally more efficient without compromising prediction performance.

  • â€¢

    We conduct extensive experiments to demonstrate the superior performance of FORKS on both adversarial and real-world datasets, while also enhancing efficiency. Furthermore, we validate FORKSâ€™s robustness and scalability using a large-scale streaming recommendation dataset.

3. FORKS: The Proposed Algorithm

In this section, we propose a novel efficient second-order online kernel learning method tailored for streaming recommendation with incremental sketching and decomposition, called FORKS.

3.1. Algorithm Overview

The streaming recommendation system needs to meet the demands of real-time performance and robustness. FigureÂ 1 depicts the overall architecture of FORKS. Rather than storing the entire kernel matrix, we apply matrix sketching techniques to approximate it with constant size. Additionally, the novel truncated incremental singular value decomposition (TISVD) method is used to generate time-varying feature mappings. This leads to incremental maintenance of both the approximate kernel matrix and the approximate feature mapping, greatly boosting efficiency. Furthermore, user feedback and interaction history are used to incrementally update the approximate kernel space, allowing the algorithm to adapt to shifts in user preferences.

3.2. Matrix Sketching for Kernel Matrix Approximation

The size of the kernel matrix grows linearly with the number of rounds, making it unsuitable for meeting the real-time demands of streaming recommendation systems. Thus, it is necessary to approximate the kernel matrix.

3.3. Novel Incremental Matrix Decomposition Method for Feature Mapping

In the previous section, we employed rank-kğ‘˜kitalic_k SVD to obtain the time-varying feature mapping; however, this method has proven inefficient in online environments. Specifically, standard rank-kğ‘˜kitalic_k SVD incurs a time complexity of Oâ¢(sp3)ğ‘‚superscriptsubscriptğ‘ ğ‘3O(s_{p}^{3})italic_O ( italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) for each update round, rendering it impractical in scenarios with a high volume of updates.

To overcome these limitations, we propose TISVD (Truncated Incremental Singular Value Decomposition), a novel incremental SVD method specifically designed for decomposing kernel sketches. TISVD provides linear time and space complexity with respect to the sketch size spsubscriptğ‘ ğ‘s_{p}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

We will begin by presenting the construction of TISVD, which is well-suited for decomposing matrices with low-rank update properties. Without loss of generality, we denote a matrix at round tğ‘¡titalic_t as

The second-order updates not only consider the gradient information but also utilize the curvature information of the loss function, leading to faster convergence rates.

At the start of a new update epoch, we incorporate a reset step before applying the gradient descent in the new embedded space. We update the feature mapping Ï•tsubscriptbold-italic-Ï•ğ‘¡\bm{\phi}_{t}bold_italic_Ï• start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT but reset ğ‘¨tsubscriptğ‘¨ğ‘¡\bm{A}_{t}bold_italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and ğ’˜tsubscriptğ’˜ğ‘¡\bm{w}_{t}bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. This step is taken to ensure that our starting point cannot be influenced by the adversary. By leveraging efficient second-order updates, we can effectively converge to the optimal hypothesis within the current subspace. Furthermore, the reset of the descent procedure when transitioning between subspaces ensures a stable starting point and maintains a bounded regret throughout the entire process. We summarize the above stages into AlgorithmÂ 2.

The incremental update of the feature mapping, combined with the reset mechanism, ensures that we can effectively capture changes in user preferences over time. More specifically, our algorithm updates the feature vector to reflect the userâ€™s current state, while resetting the Hessian matrix mitigates the influence of outdated data on the learner.

3.5. Complexity Analysis of FORKS

Given the budget of BğµBitalic_B, our FORKS consists of three parts: (1) the first stage using KOGD, (2) the updating round in the second stage, and (3) the regular round in the second stage. The main computational complexity of FORKS during the update round stems from the matrix decomposition and inversion procedures. These processes are necessary for updating the feature mapping and performing second-order gradient updates, respectively. In practical scenarios, the assumption of strong convexity may not always hold as it imposes constraints on the convexity of losses in all directions. A more feasible approach is to relax this assumption by demanding strong convexity only in the gradient direction, which is a weaker condition as indicated by the two assumptions above. For example, exp-concave losses like squared loss and squared hinge loss satisfy the condition in AssumptionÂ 2.

Remark 1.

In TheoremÂ 1, the assumption of polynomial eigenvalue decay for the kernel matrix is broadly applicable and satisfied by various types of kernels, including shift-invariant, finite-rank, and convolution kernelsÂ (Liu and Liao, 2015; Belkin, 2018). This decay property ensures that the accumulated truncated singular values of TISVD can be effectively bounded by the number of update rounds.

Remark 2.

Itâ€™s worth noting that when LCur=0subscriptğ¿Cur0L_{\mathrm{Cur}}=0italic_L start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_Cur end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, AssumptionÂ 2 essentially enforces convexity. In the worst case when LCur=0subscriptğ¿Cur0L_{\mathrm{Cur}}=0italic_L start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_Cur end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, the regret bound in the convex case degenerates to Oâ¢(T)ğ‘‚ğ‘‡O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ). The detailed proof is included in AppendixÂ D.

By configuring the update cycle as Ï=âŒŠÎ¸â¢(Tâˆ’B)âŒ‹ğœŒğœƒğ‘‡ğµ\rho=\lfloor\theta(T-B)\rflooritalic_Ï = âŒŠ italic_Î¸ ( italic_T - italic_B ) âŒ‹, where Î¸âˆˆ(0,1)ğœƒ01\theta\in(0,1)italic_Î¸ âˆˆ ( 0 , 1 ), and setting the sketch size ratio to Î³=Oâ¢(logâ¡(T)/T)ğ›¾ğ‘‚ğ‘‡ğ‘‡\gamma=O(\log(T)/\sqrt{T})italic_Î³ = italic_O ( roman_log ( italic_T ) / square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ), we derive an upper bound on regret of Oâ¢(T14â¢logâ¡T)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘‡14ğ‘‡O\left(T^{\frac{1}{4}}\log T\right)italic_O ( italic_T start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT divide start_ARG 1 end_ARG start_ARG 4 end_ARG end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman_log italic_T ) for second-order online kernel learning. In contrast, the regret bound for first-order online kernel learning is Oâ¢(T)ğ‘‚ğ‘‡O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ), while requiring a budget of B=Oâ¢(T)ğµğ‘‚ğ‘‡B=O(T)italic_B = italic_O ( italic_T )Â (Lu etÂ al., 2016a), making it less favorable than FORKS. Under the same assumption that the eigenvalues decay polynomially with rate Î²ğ›½\betaitalic_Î², the regret bound for existing second-order online kernel learning via online sampling is Oâ¢(T1Î²â¢log2â¡T)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘‡1ğ›½superscript2ğ‘‡O\left(T^{\frac{1}{\beta}}\log^{2}T\right)italic_O ( italic_T start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT divide start_ARG 1 end_ARG start_ARG italic_Î² end_ARG end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman_log start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_T )Â (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017a). Note that the regret and complexity of PROS-N-KONS are highly dependent on the eigenvalue decay rate. In practice, ensuring a rapid decay of the kernel matrix is unrealistic for streaming recommendation systems. When the matrix properties are less favorable (e.g., Î²<4ğ›½4\beta<4italic_Î² < 4), the regret of PROS-N-KONS can be worse than that of FORKS. To support our analysis, we conduct an experiment on a streaming recommendation dataset, as detailed in SectionÂ 5.3.

5. Experiments

In this section, we conduct experiments to evaluate the performance of FORKS on a wide variety of datasets. The details of datasets and experimental setup are presented in AppendixÂ E, F.

5.1. Experiments under a Fixed Budget

In this section, we demonstrate the performance of FORKS under a fixed budget, employing six widely recognized classification benchmark datasets. We compare FORKS with the existing budgeted-based online learning algorithms, including first-order algorithms RBPÂ (Cavallanti etÂ al., 2007), BPA-SÂ (Wang and Vucetic, 2010), BOGDÂ (Zhao etÂ al., 2012), FOGD, NOGDÂ (Lu etÂ al., 2016a), ProjectronÂ (Orabona etÂ al., 2008), SkeGDÂ (Zhang and Liao, 2019) and second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONSÂ (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017a). We implement the above models with the help of the LIBOL v0.3.0 toolbox toolboxÂ 111http://libol.stevenhoi.org/. All algorithms are trained using hinge loss, and their performance is measured by the average online mistake rate.

For all the algorithms, we set a fixed budget B=50ğµ50B=50italic_B = 50 for small datasets (Nâ‰¤10000)ğ‘10000(N\leq 10000)( italic_N â‰¤ 10000 ) and B=100ğµ100B=100italic_B = 100 for large datasets. Furthermore, we set buffer size B~=2â¢B,Î³=0.2formulae-sequence~ğµ2ğµğ›¾0.2\tilde{B}=2B,\gamma=0.2over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG = 2 italic_B , italic_Î³ = 0.2, sp=Bsubscriptğ‘ ğ‘ğµs_{p}=Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_B, sm=Î³â¢spsubscriptğ‘ ğ‘šğ›¾subscriptğ‘ ğ‘s_{m}=\gamma{s_{p}}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_Î³ italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, Î¸=0.3ğœƒ0.3\theta=0.3italic_Î¸ = 0.3, and update cycle Ï=âŒŠÎ¸â¢NâŒ‹ğœŒğœƒğ‘\rho=\lfloor\theta{N}\rflooritalic_Ï = âŒŠ italic_Î¸ italic_N âŒ‹ in SkeGD and FORKS if not specially specified. For algorithms with rank-kğ‘˜kitalic_k approximation, we uniformly set k=0.1â¢Bğ‘˜0.1ğµk=0.1Bitalic_k = 0.1 italic_B. Besides, we use the same experimental settings for FOGD (feature dimension = 4B). The results are presented in TableÂ 2. Our FORKS shows the best performance on most datasets and the suboptimal performance on german and ijcnn1. The update time of FORKS is comparable to that of the majority of first-order algorithms, including NOGD and SkeGD. Besides, FORKS is significantly more efficient than the existing second-order method PROS-N-KONS in large-scale datasets such as codrna and w7a.

Then, we conduct experiments to evaluate how TISVD affects the performance of the algorithm. We use the same experimental setup in codrna and vary the update rate Î¸ğœƒ\thetaitalic_Î¸ from 0.5 to 0.0005. FigureÂ 2 demonstrates that TISVD maintains efficient decomposition speed without excessively reducing performance. Furthermore, considering that frequent updates can potentially result in an elevated loss, it is essential to carefully choose an optimal update cycle that strikes a balance between achieving superior accuracy and maintaining efficiency.

5.2. Experiments under Adversarial Environment

To empirically validate the algorithms under an adversarial environment, we build adversarial datasets using the benchmark codrna and german. We compare FORKS with first-order algorithms BOGDÂ (Zhao etÂ al., 2012), SkeGDÂ (Zhang and Liao, 2019), NOGDÂ (Lu etÂ al., 2016a) and second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONSÂ (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017a) under the same budget B=200ğµ200B=200italic_B = 200. Besides, we set Î³=0.2ğ›¾0.2\gamma=0.2italic_Î³ = 0.2, sp=0.75â¢Bsubscriptğ‘ ğ‘0.75ğµs_{p}=0.75Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0.75 italic_B, sm=Î³â¢sp,k=0.1â¢Bformulae-sequencesubscriptğ‘ ğ‘šğ›¾subscriptğ‘ ğ‘ğ‘˜0.1ğµs_{m}=\gamma{s_{p}},k=0.1Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_Î³ italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_k = 0.1 italic_B and update cycle Ï=âŒŠ0.005â¢(Nâˆ’B)âŒ‹ğœŒ0.005ğ‘ğµ\rho=\lfloor 0.005(N-B)\rflooritalic_Ï = âŒŠ 0.005 ( italic_N - italic_B ) âŒ‹ in SkeGD and FORKS. Inspired by the adversarial settings inÂ (Calandriello etÂ al., 2017a; Zhang and Liao, 2019; Wang etÂ al., 2018c), we generate an online learning game with bğ‘bitalic_b blocks. At each block, we extract an instance from the dataset and repeat it for rğ‘Ÿritalic_r rounds. In addition, the labels are flipped in each even block by multiplying them with -1. We set b=500ğ‘500b=500italic_b = 500, r=10ğ‘Ÿ10r=10italic_r = 10 for codrna-1 and german-1.

Experimental results are presented in TableÂ 3. It is observed that in the adversarial environment, the performance of all methods significantly decreases with the increase of adversarial changes except for FORKS. This is due to the fact that FORKS accurately captures the concept drifting through the incremental update of the sketch matrix and the execution of rapid second-order gradient descent. Moreover, FORKS maintains its efficiency comparable to first-order algorithms, thereby ensuring that improved performance is achieved without sacrificing computational time.

5.3. Experiments on Large-Scale Datasets

In this experiment, we evaluate the efficiency and effectiveness of FORKS on streaming recommendation. We use KuaiRec, which is a real-world dataset collected from the recommendation logs of the video-sharing mobile app KuaishouÂ (Gao etÂ al., 2022). We conduct experiments on the dense matrix of KuaiRec, which consists of 4,494,57844945784,494,5784 , 494 , 578 instances with associated timestamps, making it an ideal benchmark for evaluating large-scale online learning tasks. We test the performance of the algorithm used in Section 5.3 under different budgets BğµBitalic_B ranging from 100100100100 to 500500500500. To avoid excessive training time, we use a budgeted version of PROS-N-KONS that stops updating the dictionary at a maximum budget of Bmax=100subscriptğµ100B_{\max}=100italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_max end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 100. Since the buffer size of PROS-N-KONS is data-dependent, we repeat the training process 20 times to compute the average error rate and the average time for comparison. In addition to the hinge loss, we use squared hinge loss to evaluate the performance of algorithms.

FigureÂ 3Â (a) shows the tradeoff between running time and the average mistake rate in the experiment using hinge loss. FigureÂ 3Â (b) shows the tradeoff between running time and the average mistake rate in the experiment using squared hinge loss. We observe that FORKS consistently achieves superior learning performance while maintaining comparable time costs to the other first-order algorithms, regardless of the loss functionâ€™s shape. In particular, for squared hinge loss, both PROS-N-KONS and FORKS significantly outperform first-order models, highlighting the advantages of second-order methods under exp-concave losses. Additionally, we note that FORKS exhibits significantly higher efficiency compared to the second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONS. In fact, to achieve a similar online error rate, FORKS speeds up the running time by a factor of 3333.

6. Conclusion

This paper introduces FORKS, a fast second-order online kernel learning approach. FORKS leverages incremental sketching and decomposition to efficiently manage the complex computations involved in kernel feature mapping and hypothesis updates, addressing the challenges of applying it to streaming recommendation systems. FORKS achieves a logarithmic regret bound while maintaining linear time complexity with respect to the budget. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets validate the superior scalability and robustness of FORKS, highlighting its potential for streaming recommendation tasks.

Appendix B More Discussion about TISVD

Current incremental SVD methods necessitate the prerequisite that the decomposition matrix adheres to a low-rank structureÂ (Brand, 2006). When this low-rank condition isnâ€™t met, these methods devolve into traditional SVD. However, in online learning scenarios, the assurance of a low-rank decomposed sketch matrix isnâ€™t guaranteed. In this context, TISVD innovatively accomplishes incremental maintenance of singular value matrices without relying on low-rank assumptions, rendering it adapt to online learning algorithms founded on incremental sketching methodologies.

More precisely, given the matrix ğ‘¨=ğ‘¼â¢ğšºâ¢ğ‘½âŠ¤âˆˆâ„nÃ—nğ‘¨ğ‘¼ğšºsuperscriptğ‘½topsuperscriptâ„ğ‘›ğ‘›\bm{A}=\bm{U}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times{n}}bold_italic_A = bold_italic_U bold_Î£ bold_italic_V start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT âŠ¤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT âˆˆ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n Ã— italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, the conventional incremental SVD (ISVD) streamlines the process by omitting the rotation and re-orthogonalization of ğ‘¼ğ‘¼\bm{U}bold_italic_U and ğ‘½ğ‘½\bm{V}bold_italic_V, leading to a time complexity of Oâ¢(nâ¢r+r3)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘Ÿsuperscriptğ‘Ÿ3O(nr+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). where rğ‘Ÿritalic_r denotes the matrix rank. Consequently, ISVD relies on the assumption that râ‰ªnmuch-less-thanğ‘Ÿğ‘›r\ll{n}italic_r â‰ª italic_n in order to effectively establish a linear-time SVD algorithm.

Nevertheless, in online learning scenarios, the sketch matrix earmarked for decomposition frequently fails to adhere to the low-rank characteristic, thereby rendering the direct application of ISVD ineffective in achieving linear time complexity. To counter this predicament, we have integrated truncation techniques within the framework of traditional incremental SVD methods. This adaptation yields a time complexity of Oâ¢(nâ¢rt+rt3)ğ‘‚ğ‘›subscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘¡superscriptsubscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘¡3O(nr_{t}+r_{t}^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), with rtsubscriptğ‘Ÿğ‘¡r_{t}italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT signifying the predetermined truncated rank. Crucially, this truncation innovation positions TISVD as a linear incremental SVD technique that stands independent of low-rank assumptions.

As previously discussed, applying ISVD directly to online learning algorithms isnâ€™t viable. Recognizing the substantial enhancement that accelerated decomposition feature mapping can offer to the performance of online kernel learning algorithms, prevailing research employs the randomized SVD algorithm to expedite these algorithmsÂ (Wan and Zhang, 2021; Zhang and Liao, 2019). However, itâ€™s important to highlight that, unlike the incremental SVD method, the randomized SVD is a rapid SVD technique reliant on random matrices and lacks the capability to perform incremental updates on singular value matrices. Furthermore, itâ€™s worth noting that the time complexity of randomized SVD is Oâ¢(n2â¢r+r3)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘›2ğ‘Ÿsuperscriptğ‘Ÿ3O(n^{2}r+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), which is comparatively slower than TISVDâ€™s Oâ¢(nâ¢r+r3)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘Ÿsuperscriptğ‘Ÿ3O(nr+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ).

We have compared TISVD with the rank-kğ‘˜kitalic_k truncated SVD in Section 5.2. We further construct an experiment to test the performance of randomized SVD. We initialize a random Gaussian matrix ğ‘¨âˆˆâ„100Ã—100ğ‘¨superscriptâ„100100\bm{A}\in\mathbb{R}^{100\times 100}bold_italic_A âˆˆ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 100 Ã— 100 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and use random Gaussian matrix B,Câˆˆâ„mÃ—100ğµğ¶superscriptâ„ğ‘š100B,C\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times 100}italic_B , italic_C âˆˆ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_m Ã— 100 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as low rank update. We set m=3,k=30formulae-sequenceğ‘š3ğ‘˜30m=3,k=30italic_m = 3 , italic_k = 30 and update ğ‘¨ğ‘¨\bm{A}bold_italic_A 500500500500 to 50000500005000050000 times respectively.

From FigureÂ 4, we see that TISVD continues to show desirable decomposition performance. Both TIVD and randomized SVD can reduce the size of the decomposed matrix through the low-rank approximation matrix, thereby accelerating the algorithm. However, randomized SVD enjoys a time complexity of Oâ¢(n2â¢k+k3)ğ‘‚superscriptğ‘›2ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘˜3O(n^{2}k+k^{3})italic_O ( italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), which is worse than Oâ¢(nâ¢k+k3)ğ‘‚ğ‘›ğ‘˜superscriptğ‘˜3O(nk+k^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). Besides, TISVD uses incremental updates to update the singular value matrix, which is more scalable for online learning algorithms based on incremental sketching.

The optimization error quantifies the discrepancy between the hypothesis generated by the proposed faster second-order online kernel learning algorithm and the optimal hypothesis on the incremental randomized sketches at each round. On the other hand, the estimation error measures the difference between the optimal hypotheses on the incremental randomized sketches for the first tğ‘¡titalic_t instances and for all Tğ‘‡Titalic_T instances, respectively.

To obtain an upper bound for the optimization error, we leverage the directional curvature condition presented in Assumption 2. Appendix E Dataset and Experimental Setup

We evaluate FORKS on several real-world datasets for binary classification tasks. We use several well-known classification benchmarks for online learning, where the number of instances ranges from 1000100010001000 to 581,012581012581,012581 , 012. All the experiments are performed over 20 different random permutations of the datasets. Besides, we introduce a large-scale real-world dataset KuaiRecÂ (Gao etÂ al., 2022), which has 4,494,57844945784,494,5784 , 494 , 578 instances and associated timestamps. Appendix F More about KuaiRec Dataset

For our experiment, we utilize KuaiRecâ€™s small matrix as the dataset. The processing of dependent variables involves dividing the ratio of the userâ€™s time spent on the video to the video duration (watch ratio) by a threshold of 0.75, with values greater than 0.75 classified as positive and values less than or equal to 0.75 classified as negative. The selection of independent variables is obtained from three csv files, as specified in the code.

G.1. Additional Experiment Results under Adversarial Environment

We set b=500ğ‘500b=500italic_b = 500, r=20ğ‘Ÿ20r=20italic_r = 20 for codrna-2 and german-2. The results are presented in TableÂ 4.

G.2. Additional Experiment Results under Large-Scale Real-world Datasets

Similar to the experimental setup described in section 5.3, we evaluate the performance of the algorithms across various budgets BğµBitalic_B, spanning from 100100100100 to 500500500500. To avoid excessive training time, we use a budgeted version of PROS-N-KONS with a maximum budget of Bmax=100subscriptğµ100B_{\max}=100italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_max end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 100. Since the buffer size of PROS-N-KONS is data-dependent, we repeat the training process 20202020 times to compute the average error rate and the logarithm of the average time for comparison.

From FigureÂ 5, we can observe that our FORKS show the best learning performance under most budget conditions. The large-scale experiments validate the effectiveness and efficiency of our proposed FORKS, making it potentially more practical than the existing second-order online kernel learning approaches. Meanwhile, we observed that increasing the budget size BğµBitalic_B results in a lower mistake rate but also leads to a higher computation time cost. In practice, we can flexibly adjust the budget size based on our estimates of the data stream size to obtain a better approximation quality.
